1. Average Request Duration (Average Latency)
When your manager asks for the overall average response time of your application, use this query:

promql
rate(request_duration_sum[2m]) / rate(http_requests_total[2m])

How it works:
rate(_sum[2m]) → Total time spent (in seconds) per second
rate(_total[2m]) → Number of requests per second
Dividing them gives average seconds per request

Example:
If 100 requests took 50 seconds total → Average = 0.5 seconds (500ms)
Note: Use _sum and _count / _total from Histogram or Summary metrics.

2. increase() Function
increase() calculates the total absolute increase over a time window.

Example:
promqlincrease(http_requests_total{path="/"}[3m])
Meaning: Total number of requests to / path in the last 3 minutes.

Key Difference:
FunctionOutputBest Forrate()Per second (e.g. 2.5 req/s)Graphs & trendsincrease()Total count (e.g. 750)Summary stats, billing, totals

Important Warning: Extrapolation

increase() and rate() may extrapolate values if the time window doesn't perfectly align with scrape intervals.
This can result in fractional values (e.g., 500.7 requests).
Solution: Use larger time windows ([10m], [30m], [1h]) for more accurate results.

Summary:

Use rate() for speed/velocity (good for graphs)
Use increase() for total counts
Combine _sum and _count for average latency

These two concepts (Average Latency + increase()) are heavily used in real-world monitoring.
